**Summary of Key Changes in H.R. 1 (119th Congress)**

**Sec. 100001** – **Applicability of Immigration Laws**: Establishes that all fees and provisions in Subtitle A apply to aliens in the circumstances described throughout the subtitle. Defines terms and references to the Immigration and Nationality Act (INA).

**Sec. 100002** – **Asylum Fee**: Imposes a fee for asylum applications, starting at $100 in FY2025, adjusted annually for inflation. 50% of fees go to the Executive Office for Immigration Review (EOIR), 50% to USCIS, and unallocated amounts go to the Treasury. No fee waivers allowed.

**Sec. 100003** – **Employment Authorization Document Fees**: Imposes fees for employment authorization documents for asylum applicants, parolees, and TPS holders, all starting at $550 in FY2025 and adjusted annually. Fees collected from parolees and TPS holders go to the Treasury; USCIS gets 25% of asylum-related fees for fraud prevention.

**Sec. 100004** – **Immigration Parole Fee**: Requires a $1,000 fee for parole into the U.S., with exceptions for medical emergencies, organ donation, imminent family death, etc. Fees go to the Treasury. No waivers except for specified humanitarian cases.

**Sec. 100005** – **Special Immigrant Juvenile Fee**: Imposes a $250 fee for special immigrant juvenile status applications, adjusted for inflation. All fees go to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100006** – **Temporary Protected Status Fee**: Increases the TPS fee from $50 to $500, adjusted annually. All fees go to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100007** – **Visa Integrity Fee**: Imposes a $250 fee for nonimmigrant visa issuance, adjusted annually. Fees not reimbursed go to the Treasury. Reimbursements may be granted under strict conditions.

**Sec. 100008** – **Form I-94 Fee**: Imposes a $24 fee for Form I-94, adjusted annually. 20% of fees go to the Land Border Inspection Fee Account for CBP operations; the rest to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100009** – **Annual Asylum Fee**: Imposes a $100 annual fee for each pending asylum application, adjusted annually. All fees go to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100010** – **Renewal/Extension Fee for Parolees**: Imposes a $275 fee for parolee employment authorization renewals, adjusted annually. 25% of fees go to USCIS, the rest to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100011** – **Renewal/Extension Fee for Asylum Applicants**: Imposes a $275 fee for asylum employment authorization renewals. Employment authorization terminates under specific conditions. 25% of fees go to USCIS, the rest to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100012** – **Renewal/Extension Fee for TPS Aliens**: Imposes a $275 fee for TPS employment authorization renewals, adjusted annually. 25% of fees go to USCIS, the rest to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100013** – **Adjustment of Status Fees**: Imposes fees for adjustment of status, waivers of inadmissibility, TPS applications, and appeals. Fees range from $600 to $1,500, adjusted annually. Up to 25% of fees are transferred to EOIR; the rest to the Treasury. No use for the Legal Orientation Program.

**Sec. 100014** – **Electronic System for Travel Authorization (ESTA) Fee**: Increases the ESTA fee to at least $13, adjusted annually. Extends the validity period to October 31, 2034. No waivers.

**Sec. 100015** – **Electronic Visa Update System (EVUS) Fee**: Imposes a $30 fee for EVUS enrollment, adjusted annually. $5 per payment is deposited into a dedicated CBP account for EVUS administration; the rest to the Treasury. No waivers.

**Sec. 100016** – **Fee for Aliens Removed in Absentia**: Imposes a $5,000 fee for aliens ordered removed in absentia who are later arrested. Fees go to ICE’s Detention and Removal Office. No waivers.

**Sec. 100017** – **Inadmissible Alien Apprehension Fee**: Imposes a $5,000 fee for inadmissible aliens apprehended between ports of entry. Fees go to ICE’s Detention and Removal Office. No waivers.

**Sec. 100018** – **Amendment to Asylum Application Authority**: Changes the asylum application authority from discretionary (“may”) to mandatory (“shall”) and removes the cap on adjudication and naturalization fees.

**Sec. 100051** – **DHS Appropriation**: Provides $2.055 billion for DHS in FY2025, available through 2029. Funds include hiring CBP agents, removal operations, background checks, DNA/fingerprint collection, state/local participation, and IT upgrades.

**Sec. 100052** – **ICE Appropriation**: Provides $29.85 billion for ICE in FY2025, available through 2029. Funds include hiring, retention/signing bonuses, recruitment, transportation, facility upgrades, family unity, 287(g) agreements, and the Victims of Immigration Crime Engagement Office.

**Sec. 100053** – **Federal Law Enforcement Training Centers Appropriation**: Provides $750 million for FLETC in FY2025, available through 2029. $285 million for training new law enforcement personnel; $465 million for facility upgrades and equipment.

**Sec. 100054** – **DOJ Appropriation**: Provides $3.33 billion for DOJ in FY2025, available through 2029. Funds include EOIR staffing, drug trafficking prosecution, immigration crime enforcement, nonparty injunctions, Byrne grants, and compensation for incarcerating criminal aliens.

**Sec. 100055** – **BIDEN Reimbursement Fund**: Establishes a $3.5 billion fund within DOJ to reimburse states and local governments for immigration enforcement costs. Funds can be used for locating criminal aliens, gang enforcement, court operations, and transportation.

**Sec. 100056** – **Bureau of Prisons Appropriation**: Provides $5 billion for BOP in FY2025, available through 2029. $3 billion for hiring and training staff; $2 billion for facility maintenance and repairs.

**Sec. 100057** – **U.S. Secret Service Appropriation**: Provides $1.17 billion for USSS in FY2025, available through 2029. Funds include personnel, training, technology, and retention/signing bonuses.

**Sec. 100101** – **Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts Appropriation**: Provides $1.25 million annually through 2028 for analyzing and reporting on judicial orders against the federal government.

**Sec. 100102** – **Federal Judicial Center Appropriation**: Provides $1 million annually through 2028 for training on constitutional limitations and cost mitigation strategies for non-party injunctions.

**Sec. 100201** – **RECA Fund Extension**: Extends the Radiation Exposure Compensation Act (RECA) fund to December 31, 2028.

**Sec. 100202** – **Atmospheric Testing Claims**: Expands eligibility for leukemia claims related to nuclear testing, including physical presence in affected areas and updated disease definitions. Increases compensation to $100,000.

**Sec. 100203** – **Uranium Mining Claims**: Expands eligibility for uranium miners, millers, and transporters, including combined work histories and chronic renal diseases. Updates definitions and compensation rules.

**Sec. 100204** – **Manhattan Project Waste Claims**: Establishes a new compensation framework for individuals exposed to Manhattan Project waste, including specified diseases and affected ZIP codes. Provides $25,000 for survivors.

**Sec. 100205** – **RECA Claims Limitations**: Moves the deadline for filing RECA claims from December 31, 2027, to December 31, 2027 (no change). [end of text]


